In addition, a matched-pairs comparison of dominant and subordinate male song performances sampled on the same day and in the same social group and outside of the within-group laying period showed that dominant males sang for significantly longer than subordinates on days when both males sang (paired 
   t-test: t = 4.79, n = 10 paired males, p < 0.001; 
   Fig. 4a).
